Housing Subsidy Algorithm for Emil City

Jasmine Siyu Wu

11/5/2021


Source: Cayman Homes Construction


1. Introduction

Over the past twenty years, the Emil City Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) has been running a home repair tax credit program. There is no doubt that home repair subsidy programs have considerable benefits to both homeowners and neighborhoods, yet this program has not been fully in use. The conversion rate of the eligible homeowners that have been reached out is inadequate, while the resources of outreach are limited. To more precisely target eligible homeowners who are more likely to take the credit, the HCD now wants to build a model based on the previous campaign information and results to better allocate the limited outreach resources to certain types of homeowners. In this analysis, we will further use the built model for a cost/benefit analysis to assist the agency’s decision-making.

2. Exploratory Analysis

HCD provides a random record sample from the previous campaigns (N = 4,119), of which 451 (10.9%) homeowners took the credit and 3,668 (89.1%) did not take the credit. Each homeowner is attached with some variables, including numeric variables and categorical variables.

Figure 2.1 shows the means of numeric features associated with the likelihood of taking the credit. As can be seen in the figures, the average age (age) of homeowners taking the credit is slightly higher than the homeowners not taking it. The average contacts for this campaign (campaign) are higher for homeowners not taking the credit, while the number of contacts before this campaign (previous) is higher for homeowners taking the credit. In terms of economic characteristics, two homeowner groups have similar mean consumer price index (cons.price.idx) and consumer confidence index (cons.conf.idx). Homeowners who took the credit show a lower average inflation rate (inflation_rate) and a negative unemployment rate (unemploy_rate), which is confusing. We need to examine the distribution of these numeric variables to better understand variances between two homeowner groups.

housingSub %>%
  dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, cons.conf.idx, inflation_rate, spent_on_repairs) %>%
  gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    ggplot(aes(y, value, fill=y)) + 
      geom_bar(position = "dodge", stat = "summary", fun.y = "mean") + 
      facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
      scale_fill_manual(values = palette2) +
      labs(x="Uptake of Credit", y="Value", 
           title = "Feature associations with the likelihood of taking the credit",
           subtitle = "Numeric features",
           caption = "Figure 2.1") +
  plotTheme()


As shown in Figure 2.2, the uptake of credit are associated with age groups.Homeowners taking the credit have a smaller share of the 30-to-50-years and larger share of the over-50-years. While Figure 2.1 shows merely no difference between average consumer price index (cons.price.idx) and consumer confidence index (cons.conf.idx), we can see more even distribution of these indexes in homeowners taking the credit. That is, for some sub-ranges of these indexes, homeowners taking the credit have a noticeable smaller presence than the other group, which may be a differentiator between them. As for the inflation rate (inflation_rate), homeowners not taking the credit have a peak of high inflation rates, echoing with their higher average inflation rate in Figure 2.1. Lastly, it is still hard to understand why negative values appear in the unemployment rate (unemploy_rate), so we will be cautious to use this variable as a predictor in the model.

housingSub %>%
    dplyr::select(y, age, campaign, previous, unemploy_rate, cons.price.idx, cons.conf.idx, inflation_rate, spent_on_repairs) %>%
    gather(Variable, value, -y) %>%
    ggplot() +

    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
    scale_color_manual(values = palette2) +
    labs(title = "Feature distributions: uptake vs. no uptake",
         subtitle = "Numeric features",
         caption = "Figure 2.2") +
  plotTheme()


There are also some categorical features attached to homeowners. Figure 2.3 shows the counts of each categorical feature by the uptake of the credit. There are no noticeable associations between whether or not taking the credit with the type of contact (contact) used to reach out homeowners, day of the week of last contact (day_of_week), marital status (marital), mortgage (mortgage), and tax lien (taxLien). However, we can see that homeowners’ uptake of the credit is related to some education levels (education), job types (job), months of the last contact (month), days after the last contact (pdays), and previous marketing campaign results (poutcome). These can be used as independent variables in the model.

housingSub %>%
    dplyr::select(y, job, marital, education, taxLien, mortgage, taxbill_in_phl,

3. Logistic Regression

In this analysis, we use logit regression to predict the binomial variable. Our dependent variable is y_numeric, of which 0 means “not taking the credit” and 1 means “taking the credit”. The data is split into 65/35 training/test set in this analysis, meaning that roughly 2680 records are used for training the logit model while the rest 1440 records are used to test the accuracy and generalizability of the model.


3.1. Kitchen Sink Model

The first model uses most of the original variables coming with the data. As the summary shows, its McFadden (pseudo-\(R^{2}\)) is 0.218, implying an undesired predicting power of the model.

Using the first model to predict the test set, we see that most of the negative events (0’s) (not taking the credit) can be well predicted as the “hump” is around 0. However, only a small portion of positive events (1’s) (taking the credit) have probabilities close to 1, and the “hump” is far away from 1, in fact around 0. That is, this “kitchen sink” model has a weak predicting power of positive events (0’s).

Besides McFadden (pseudo-\(R^{2}\)), Sensitivity and Specificity also measure the goodness of Fit of a logit model. As the summary below shows, the Sensitivity and Specificity of housingSubModel is 0.1975 and 0.9867, respectively. Therefore, only 19.75% of all positives (0’s) can be explained by our model, while 98.67% of all negatives (0’s) can be explained by the model.

To further test the generalizability of the first model, we run a 100 k-fold cross validation and output predicted probabilities. Since the dependent variable in the cross-validation is y instead of y_numeric, the Sensitivity and Specificity are reversed. The results show that the generalized model has a Sensitivity of 0.985 and a Specificity of 0.221. That is, the first model in general can explain 22.1% of all positives (taking the credit) and 98.5% of all negatives (not taking the credit). The area under the ROC curve (known as AUC) is 0.76, suggesting the model has some substantial predicting power.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

cvFit_1 <- train(y ~ .,
                  data=housingSub %>% 
                    dplyr::select(-age, marital, -mortgage, -contact, -day_of_week, -pdays, -unemploy_rate, 
                                  -y_numeric), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl)

Figure 3.1 displays the distribution of the results of all 100 folds of cross-validation. Most of folds have an ROC over 0.5, reassuring the model’s predicting power. The Specificity has some occasional values over 0.5, implying the inconsistency of associations between the independent variables and the positives (1’s) in the original data. Also, since the positives (1’s) only take 10% of the data, they tend to have a larger variance than the negatives (0’s).

3.2. New Model with Engineered Features

To improve the “kitchen sink” model, this section engineers new features based on the observations in 2. Exploratory Analysis.

Firstly, some numeric features are re-classfied as categorical features. previous_bi is a binary variable developed upon pdays: 1 means the homeowner has been contacted before, and 0 mean not. age_group is a multi-categorical variable derived from age: under 30 years old are YoungAdult, between 30 and 50 years old are MiddleAge, and over 50 years old are OldAdult. retired_bi is a dummy variable derived from job: 1 means the individual is retired, and 0 means not.

Secondly, some numeric variables are transformed in the model, such as log(spent_on_repairs+1), log(inflation_rate), and I(abs(unemploy_rate)^-1). Their associations with the dependent variable increase after transformations.

In comparison to the first model, the new engineered model has a similar McFadden (pseudo-\(R^{2}\)), 0.2135. As Figure 3.3 shows, this new model has a few more predicted probabilities close to 1, suggesting a slightly better predicting power of positives.

housingSub <- housingSub %>%
  mutate(previous_bi = ifelse(pdays < 999, "1", "0"),
         highschool = case_when(education %in% c("basic.4y", "basic.6y", "basic.9y", "illiterate") ~ "Yes",
                                education %in% c("high.school", "professional.course", "university.degree") ~ "No",
                                education == "unknown" ~ "unknown"),
         season = case_when(month %in% c("may", "jun", "jul", "aug")  ~ "Summer",
                            month %in% c("mar", "apr", "sep", "oct", "nov", "dec")  ~ "Other"),
         age_group = case_when(age < 30 ~ "YoungAdult",
                               age >= 30 & age < 50  ~ "MiddleAge",
                               age >= 50  ~ "OldAdult"),
         p_success = ifelse(poutcome == "success", "Yes", "No"),
         retired_bi = ifelse(job == "retired", "Yes", "No"))


set.seed(1234)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(housingSub$y_numeric, p = .65,
                                  list = FALSE,
                                  times = 1)
housingSubTrain_2 <- housingSub[ trainIndex,]
housingSubTest_2  <- housingSub[-trainIndex,]



housingSubModel_2 <- glm(y_numeric ~ marital + education + month + previous_bi + age_group + previous +
                           log(spent_on_repairs+1) + log(inflation_rate) + retired_bi + I(abs(unemploy_rate)^-1), 
                         data=housingSubTrain_2 %>% 
                           dplyr::select(-X, -mortgage, -age, -day_of_week, -pdays, -contact,
                                         -y, -taxLien, -cons.price.idx, -cons.conf.idx,
                                         -job, -taxbill_in_phl, -highschool, -poutcome, -season,
                                         -campaign, -p_success),
                  family="binomial" (link="logit"))

4. Cost/Benefit Analysis

Based on the second model, we will conduct a cost/benefit analysis for Emil City’s housing tax credit program considering marketing costs, individual benefits, and social benefits. Some assumptions of costs and benefits from the HCD are:

  • The marketing costs $2,850 per homeowner for staff and resources to facilitate mailers, phone calls, and information/counselling sessions.
  • The credit costs $5,000 per homeowner which can be used toward home improvement.
  • Each house after taking the credit will be sold with a $10,000 premium.
  • Each house after taking the credit will bring an aggregate premium of $56,000 for the surrounding houses.


Given the assumptions above, we formulate the revenues and uptake of credits for each confusion metric:

     False negative (FN) revenue* : predicted incorrectly homeowner would not take the credit
  • actualCredit = Count * 0
  • Revenue = $0
     False positive (FP) revenue : predicted incorrectly homeowner would take the credit
  • actualCredit = Count * 0
  • Revenue = ($0 - $2850) * Count
     True negative (TN) revenue : predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit
  • actualCredit = Count * 0
  • Revenue = $0
     True positive (TP) revenue** : predicted correctly homeowner would take the credit
  • actualCredit = Count * 0
  • Revenue = ($0 - $2850) * Count * 0.75 + ($10000 + $56000 - $2850 - $5000) * Count * 0.25


* Although these homeowners took the housing tax credit, yet their decisions were not related to the marketing campaign. We zero out this category, assuming the cost/benefit and credit of this are 0.

** We assume that 25% of contacted eligible homeowners take the credit, and the remainder (75%) received the marketing allocation but do not take the credit.


Applying the above formulas to each confusion metric, we can calculate the total revenue of each category (see Table 4.1). In the test set (n = 1,441), 38 are correctly predicted to take the credit (True_Positive), generating a total revenue of $471,200. Meanwhile, 23 are incorrectly predicted to take the credit (False_Positive), costing $65,550 in total. The rest two categories have no cost and benefit. Note, all of these predictions are under the default threshold of 0.50.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs_2 %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", 0 * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", ((-2850) * (Count * .75)) + ((56000+10000-2850-5000) * (Count * .25)),
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0 * Count,  # zero out this category
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0))))) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We correctly predicted no uptake of credit",
              "We correctly predicted an uptake of credit",
              "We predicted no uptake but houseowner took the credit",
              "We predicted an uptake but houseowner did not take the credit")))

kable(cost_benefit_table,
       caption = "Table 4.1 Cost/Benefit Table") %>% kable_styling()

5. Optimizing Thresholds

The last step to tuning our model is to optimize the threshold of our logit model. Figure 5.1 shows the total revenue and total credits of each confusion metric for each threshold. For true positives , total revenue and total credits decrease as the threshold increases. Also, the cost of false positives decreases as the threshold increases. This is because we cannot predict the uptake of credit well at high thresholds. Therefore, the maximum total revenue should be attained at a lower threshold, where the model can predict more correct uptake of credit.

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs_2, observedClass = Outcome, predictedProbs = Probs)

whichThreshold <- 
  whichThreshold %>%
    dplyr::select(starts_with("Count"), Threshold) %>%
    gather(Variable, Count, -Threshold) %>%
    mutate(Revenue = case_when(Variable == "Count_TN" ~ 0 * Count,
                               Variable == "Count_TP" ~ (-2850) * Count * .75 + (56000+10000-2850-5000) * Count * .25,
                               Variable == "Count_FN" ~ 0 * Count,  # zero out this category
                               Variable == "Count_FP" ~ (-2850) * Count),
           actualCredit = ifelse(Variable == "Count_TP", (Count * .25), 0))


ggarrange(ncol=2,
  whichThreshold %>%
    ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, Revenue, colour = Variable)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_colour_manual(values = palette4) +    #5, 
    labs(title = "Revenue by confusion matrix type and threshold",
         y = "Revenue",
         caption = "Figure 5.1") +
    plotTheme() + theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 14, hjust=0)) +
    guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix")),
  
  whichThreshold %>%
    ggplot(.,aes(Threshold, actualCredit, colour = Variable)) +
    geom_point() +
    scale_colour_manual(values = palette4) +    #5, 
    labs(title = "Credits by confusion matrix type and threshold",
         y = "Credits",
         caption = " ") +
    plotTheme() + theme(plot.caption = element_text(size = 14, hjust=0)) +
    guides(colour=guide_legend(title = "Confusion Matrix")),
  common.legend = TRUE, legend="right")


Summing revenues and credits up of all confusion metrics, we are able to find the optimal threshold, where the total revenue of the housing tax credit campaign program reaches the highest value. As the left plot of Figure 5.2 shows, the total revenue has its peak around the 15% threshold. That means, when the model classify all predicted possibilities over 0.15 as “taking the credit”, the HCD is likely to have the highest gaining from the campaign. Before a certain threshold (around 0.06), the total revenue is negative. After the optimal threshold, the total revenue decreases and approaches $0. The right plot echos the right side of Figure 5.1, of which only true positives are counted as total credits and decrease when the threshold increases. Its peak is around 0.01, meaning that only when the model classify everything as “taking the credit”, it can capture all positives (taking credits) in the real life.

whichThreshold_revenue <- whichThreshold %>% 
    group_by(Threshold) %>% 
    summarize(Revenue = sum(Revenue),
              Total_Credits = sum(actualCredit),
              Actual_Credit_Rate = sum(actualCredit) / sum(Count))

grid.arrange(ncol=2,
  ggplot(whichThreshold_revenue)+
    geom_line(aes(x = Threshold, y = Revenue))+
    geom_vline(xintercept =  pull(arrange(whichThreshold_revenue, -Revenue)[1,1]))+
      labs(title = "Model Revenues By Threshold For Test Sample",
           subtitle = "Vertical Line Denotes Optimal Threshold",
           y="Total Revenue ($)"),
    
  ggplot(whichThreshold_revenue)+
    geom_line(aes(x = Threshold, y = Total_Credits))+

Table 5.1 compares the 50% threshold and the optimal threshold (15%). Of all 1,441 homeowners in the test set, the optimal threshold can correctly predict 22.5 homeowners taking the credits and result in $771,150 revenue. The 50% threshold can only correctly predict 9.5 homeowners taking the credits and result in $405,650 revenue. Once again, this shows that when setting the threshold low, this model can predict more correct credits being taken in reality, which lead to more revenues for homeowners and society.

6. Conclusion

In conclusion, the engineered model should be put into production although with a low Sensitivity. It can only explain less than 25% of all uptakes of the housing tax credit in the past. The unexplained portion (75%) of people who take credits will cause the waste of marketing resources. However, this model is still instructive if setting a low threshold, when it generates considerable total revenues. This is a significant gaining for residents and the city.

If we can improve the model’s predicting power of positives (taking the credit), we can ensure better use of HCD’s budget and further increase the total revenue. Several methods can be utilized to make the model better. First of all, the agency can collect more important features of houses and homeowners, such as house size, house age, and renovation rate of the neighborhood. Secondly, we can use a larger sample or simulate positives to increase the share of positives in the dataset. Lastly, we can attempt new prediction models, such as neural networks. To increase the response rate, the HCD staff can change the contact time. For instance, phone calls are more likely to be picked up on weekends. Learning the homeowners who took the credit in the past gives us an opportunity to improve targeted marketing strategies.
